<fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
  <fr:frontmatter>
    <fr:anchor>2176</fr:anchor>
    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5</fr:addr>
    <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml</fr:route>
    <fr:authors />
    <fr:number>5.2.5</fr:number>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  X_\bullet \to  Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of simplicial topological spaces.
    The functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*\colon \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )\to \mathrm {D}^+(Y_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> can be calculated "component by component": if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is a complex of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, then to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*K]]></fr:tex> we take a resolution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\xrightarrow {\sim } K']]></fr:tex> such that the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i {u_p}_*(F^p)=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>0]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex> (cf. (III) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />);
    then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*K\approx  u_*K']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2177</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Cohomological descent › Cohomology of simplicial topological spaces"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii-5" title="Hodge Theory III › Cohomological descent"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Cohomological descent</fr:link> › Cohomology of simplicial topological spaces</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2133</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.1</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>To each simplicial topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is associated a usual topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|X_\bullet |]]></fr:tex>, called its geometric realisation (see below).
    In the particular case where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are discrete, we recover the usual notion of geometric realisation of a simplicial set.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>In [<fr:link type="local" href="S1968.xml" addr="S1968" title="Classifying spaces and spectral sequences">S1968</fr:link>], G. Segal defined the cohomology of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> with values in an abelian group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (|X_\bullet |,A)]]></fr:tex>.
    Under suitable hypotheses, the filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|X_\bullet |]]></fr:tex> by successive skeletons gives a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>442</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.1.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,A)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,A).       \tag{5.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>One of the interests in using this definition is that it also applies, for example, to the definition of the groups <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
    We will adopt another definition, which is better adapted to sheaf-theoretic techniques.</fr:p>
                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>443</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="machine">#266</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>unstable-266.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:title text="Geometric realisation">Geometric realisation</fr:title>
                    <fr:authors />
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>For an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex>, we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex> the simple in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^{\Delta _n}]]></fr:tex> whose vertices are the set of basis vectors.
      We identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta _n]]></fr:tex> with the set of vertices of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex>.
      Every function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \Delta _n\to \Delta _m]]></fr:tex> extends by linearity to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f|\colon |\Delta _n|\to |\Delta _m|]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial topological space.
      Let
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         Y=\coprod _{n\geqslant 0}(X_n\times |\Delta _n|).       ]]></fr:tex>
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be the finest equivalence relation on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> for which, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \Delta _n\to \Delta _m]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Delta )]]></fr:tex>, any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_m\in  X_m]]></fr:tex>, and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in |\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex>, we have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         (x_m,|f|(a))         \equiv  (f(x_m),a)         \operatorname {mod} R.       ]]></fr:tex>
      The <fr:em>geometric realisation</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is by definition
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         |X_\bullet |         = Y/R.       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2134</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.2</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial topological space.
    The functors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^i(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex> of <fr:em>cohomology with coefficients in the abelian sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex></fr:em> are the derived functors of the functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.13.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.13.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.13.1" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>This definition is equivalent to the following, sometimes more convenient.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2135</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.3</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We can show (by example, using (III) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />) that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> always admits resolutions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> on the right such that
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^r(X_q,K^{p,q})       =0       \quad \text {for } p,q\geqslant 0 \text { and } r>0.     ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is such a resolution, then we canonically have that

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2084</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )         \simeq  \operatorname {H}^n(\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)).       \tag{5.2.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    It is easy to show directly that the right-hand side is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>;
    for what follows, we are free to <fr:em>define</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex> by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    We can further show that the spectral sequence of the complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)]]></fr:tex>, filtered by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.9.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" /> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>)

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2085</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,F^p)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )       \tag{5.2.3.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.1.1" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2136</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.4</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We will need to make precise the above construction when passing to derived categories, and to give a relative variant of it.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the constant simplicial space defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> with augmentation map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon \colon  S_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_\bullet \colon  X_\bullet \to  S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the map induced by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>.
    Then

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2137</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.4.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         a_*         = \varepsilon _* {a_\bullet }_*\colon          (X_\bullet )^\sim          \to  (S)^\sim .       \tag{5.2.4.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The derived version of this equation is

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2138</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.4.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R} a_*         = \mathrm {R}\varepsilon _* \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*\colon          \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+(S)         \to  (S)^\sim .       \tag{5.2.4.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> is the bounded-below derived category of the category of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We will calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\varepsilon _*]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2139</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.5</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  X_\bullet \to  Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of simplicial topological spaces.
    The functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*\colon \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )\to \mathrm {D}^+(Y_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> can be calculated "component by component": if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is a complex of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, then to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*K]]></fr:tex> we take a resolution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\xrightarrow {\sim } K']]></fr:tex> such that the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i {u_p}_*(F^p)=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>0]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex> (cf. (III) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />);
    then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} u_*K\approx  u_*K']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2140</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.6</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}\colon \operatorname {C}^+(S_\bullet )\to \operatorname {C}^+(S)]]></fr:tex> sends acyclic complexes to acyclic complexes.
    It thus trivially derives to
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \mathrm {s}\colon  \mathrm {D}^+(S_\bullet )       \to  \mathrm {D}^+(S).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is an injective sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, then the chain complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s} F]]></fr:tex> is a resolution of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _*F]]></fr:tex>.
    We thus obtain an isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\varepsilon _*\xrightarrow {\sim }\mathrm {s}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.4.2" /> becomes

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2141</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.6.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.6.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.6.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R} a_*         = \mathrm {s}\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*       \tag{5.2.6.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2142</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>5.2.7</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Combined with <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml" number="5.2.5" /> and specialised to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>, this equation proves <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    In concrete terms, this implies that, to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex>, we can proceed in two steps:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        We take a resolution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\xrightarrow {\sim } K']]></fr:tex> such that the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i {a_p}_*(F^p)=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>0]]></fr:tex>.
        The complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K'\in \mathrm {D}^+(S_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> (the derived category of the category of cosimplicial abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>) can be identified with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*K]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex> is the simple complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex> associated to the double complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.2" /> generalises to a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2087</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.7.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \mathrm {R}^q{a_p}_*(K|X_p)         \Rightarrow  \mathrm {R}^{p+q}a_*K       \tag{5.2.7.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    induced by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" />.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2178</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2.7</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Combined with <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml" number="5.2.5" /> and specialised to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>, this equation proves <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    In concrete terms, this implies that, to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex>, we can proceed in two steps:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        We take a resolution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\xrightarrow {\sim } K']]></fr:tex> such that the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i {a_p}_*(F^p)=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>0]]></fr:tex>.
        The complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K'\in \mathrm {D}^+(S_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> (the derived category of the category of cosimplicial abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>) can be identified with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*K]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex> is the simple complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex> associated to the double complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
            <fr:p>The spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.2" /> generalises to a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2087</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.7.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \mathrm {R}^q{a_p}_*(K|X_p)         \Rightarrow  \mathrm {R}^{p+q}a_*K       \tag{5.2.7.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    induced by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" />.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2179</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.1.12</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.12.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>8.1.12</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a smooth proper scheme (over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>), and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a normal crossing divisor in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet =X_\bullet \setminus  Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, and we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> the inclusion of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    The constructions in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.8" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.8.xml" taxon="Scholium" number="8.1.8" /> can be performed "uniformly in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex>", as <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml" number="5.2.5" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.7" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.7.xml" taxon="Lemma" number="6.2.7" /> show.
    
    They thus give a cohomological mixed Hodge complex
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \big (\mathrm {R} j_*\mathbb {Z}, (\mathrm {R} j_*\mathbb {Q},\tau _{\leqslant }), (\Omega _{X_\bullet }^\bullet (\log  Y_\bullet ),W,F)\big )     ]]></fr:tex>
    on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2180</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Examples</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.1.9</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(I) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial analytic space.
      The structure sheaves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{X_n}]]></fr:tex> form a sheaf of rings on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(II) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial analytic space augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      The sheaves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _{X_n/S}^1]]></fr:tex> form a sheaf of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex>-modules on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      Its <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>-th exterior power is the sheaf of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex>-modules <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Omega _{X_n/S}^i)_{n\geqslant 0}]]></fr:tex> denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _{X_\bullet {/}S}^i]]></fr:tex>.
      
      The de Rham complexes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Omega _{X_n/S}^\bullet )_{n\geqslant 0}]]></fr:tex> form a complex of sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(III) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a sheaf of abelian groups on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      The canonical flasque Godement resolutions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}^\bullet (F^n)]]></fr:tex> form a complex of sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> that is a resolution of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(IV) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a topological space.
      Sheaves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on the constant simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> can be identified with cosimplicial sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      In particular, an abelian sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> defines a chain complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(F^n,d=\sum _i(-1)^i\delta _i)]]></fr:tex>.
      A complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> defines a double complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K^{n,m})]]></fr:tex> that we again denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (here <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> is the cosimplicial degree) and whose associated simple complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{K}]]></fr:tex> is

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2057</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.9.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           (\mathrm {s}{K})^n           = \bigoplus _{p+q=n} K^{pq}         \tag{5.1.9.1}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      with differential given by

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2058</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.9.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \mathrm {d}(x^{pq})           = \mathrm {d}_K(x^{pq}) + (-1)^p\sum _i(-1)^i\delta _i x^{pq}.         \tag{5.1.9.2}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      We denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> the second filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{K}]]></fr:tex>, i.e.

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2059</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.9.3</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           L^r(\mathrm {s}{K})           = \bigoplus _{q\geqslant  r} K^{pq}.         \tag{5.1.9.3}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
